<div class="outer-layout-container">

<main class="layout-content layout-container" >

  
  


      <div class="layout-content-full">
      <div>
    <div data-drupal-messages-fallback class="hidden"></div>

  </div>

    </div>  
    
  <div class="layout-container--grid layout-container--has-left-rail layout-container--has-right-rail retain-ltr-area-order">
    <div class="layout-content-main">
        <div>
    <div id="block-pt-content" class="block">
  
    
      

<!-- is_first_page: 1 -->
<!-- recent_posts_offset: 0 -->
<!-- recent_posts_items_per_page: 10 -->
<!-- recent_posts: 1 -->
  <!-- recent_posts_argument: 5013373+5012774+5008728+5008241 -->
  <!-- recent_posts_argument: 5000077 -->
<article data-history-node-id="5000077" role="article" class="basics-full">
  <div class="content-header d-flex reference-header">
              <div class="content-header--image">
        
            <article>
  
      
              <img src="https://cdn2.psychologytoday.com/assets/styles/manual_crop_1_1_75x75/public/2019-12/shutterstock_278969585%20%281%29.jpg?itok=GZOpna3Z" width="75" height="75" alt="rangizzz/Shutterstock" title="rangizzz/Shutterstock" loading="lazy" />



      
  </article>

      
      </div>
    
    <div class="content-header--text">
                    <h1 class="reference__title section-title">Video Game Addiction</h1>
                          <p class="content-header--synonyms text-teaser-byline">Gaming Disorder</p>
      
                    <p class="reference__review-info fine-print">
          <a href="/us/docs/editorial-process" class="reference__review-info-link">
            <span class="reference__review-info-icon"></span>
            <span class="reference__review-info-text">Reviewed by Psychology Today Staff</span>
          </a>
        </p>
          </div>
  </div>

  <div>
                                              
              <div class="reference__body">
        
<div class="field-name-body">
                    <p dir="ltr">A gaming disorder, sometimes referred to as &ldquo;video game <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/addiction" title="Psychology Today looks at addiction" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">addiction</a>,&rdquo; is a pattern of game-playing behavior&mdash;involving online gaming or offline video games&mdash;that is difficult to control and that continues unabated despite serious negative consequences in other areas of the gamer&rsquo;s life.</p>
            </div>

      </div>
    
          
      <div class="table-of-contents border-top">
        <h4 class="table-of-contents--title">Contents</h4>
        <ul>
                      <li class="table-of-contents--item">
              <a href="#the-debate-over-video-game-addiction">
                The Debate Over Video Game Addiction
              </a>
            </li>
                      <li class="table-of-contents--item">
              <a href="#when-is-gaming-a-mental-health-problem">
                When Is Gaming a Mental Health Problem?
              </a>
            </li>
                      <li class="table-of-contents--item">
              <a href="#children-and-video-games">
                Children and Video Games
              </a>
            </li>
                  </ul>
      </div>
    
                
          <div class="reference__sections">
        <div>
      <div>  <div class="section section--separator">
          <div id="the-debate-over-video-game-addiction" class="section-anchor skip-inline-link-filter"></div>
                      <div class="h2 section-title">
            The Debate Over Video Game <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/addiction" title="Psychology Today looks at Addiction" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">Addiction</a>
      </div>
        <div class="section__body">
                      
            <article>
  
      
              <img src="https://cdn2.psychologytoday.com/assets/styles/manual_crop_1_1_180x180/public/2021-06/shutterstock_1810292188.jpg?itok=Efg1N9N7" width="180" height="180" alt="Prostock-studio/Shutterstock" title="Prostock-studio/Shutterstock" loading="lazy" />



      
  </article>

      
                    
            <p dir="ltr">Experts debate whether severely problematic gaming truly constitutes an &ldquo;addiction&rdquo; in the same sense as drug and <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/alcohol" title="Psychology Today looks at alcohol" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">alcohol</a> addictions. But disordered gaming behavior recently received official recognition as a mental health condition by the World Health Organization (WHO), which included &ldquo;gaming disorder&rdquo; in the 11th edition of its <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/international-classification-of-diseases-icd" title="Psychology Today looks at International Classification of Diseases" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">International Classification of Diseases</a> (ICD-11). According to that guide, gaming disorder is marked by &ldquo;impaired control&rdquo; over gaming, which leads to it taking priority over other interests and activities. The gaming behavior persists even as it causes &ldquo;significant impairment&rdquo; in areas such as personal relationships, school, or work. </p>
<p dir="ltr">While gaming disorder is not officially included in the <em><a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/dsm" title="Psychology Today looks at Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders</a></em>, widely used for behavioral health diagnoses in the U.S., the latest version of the manual&mdash;the DSM-5&mdash;refers to Internet Gaming Disorder as a condition for further study.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Among the tentative criteria for such a disorder are withdrawal symptoms, such as irritability or sadness, when Internet gaming ceases; tolerance, or an increasing need for gaming; <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/deception" title="Psychology Today looks at deception" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">deception</a> about the amount of one&rsquo;s gaming; and failed attempts to control one&rsquo;s gaming.</p>
      
        </div>
          
          
<div class="faqs">
                                                            <div class="faq faq--1">
                <div itemscope  itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
          <div class="faq--title d-flex">
        <div itemprop="name" class="h3 faq--question">
          
            What are the criticisms of gaming disorder?
      
        </div>
        <div class="faq--control-container">
          <button class="faq--control">
            <div class="faq--control-icon">
              <svg width="13px" height="8px" viewBox="0 0 13 8" version="1.1"
     xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
     xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
                <!-- Generator: Sketch 46.2 (44496) - http://www.bohemiancoding.com/sketch -->
                <desc>Created with Sketch.</desc>
                <defs></defs>
                <g id="-small" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd">
                  <g id="Tests---Listing-Page---SM"
                     transform="translate(-490.000000, -597.000000)" fill="#2C2D30">
                    <g id="Left-col" transform="translate(74.000000, 162.000000)">
                      <g id="Table" transform="translate(0.000000, 426.000000)">
                        <polygon id="navigatedown"
                                 points="422.310547 16.3125 428.621094 10.0019531 427.62793 9 422.310547 14.3173828 416.993164 9 416 10.0019531"></polygon>
                      </g>
                    </g>
                  </g>
                </g>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div itemscope="" itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer" class="faq--answer">
        <div itemprop="text">
          
            <p>Experts are critical of creating a gaming disorder diagnosis for several reasons. One is the <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/fear" title="Psychology Today looks at fear" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">fear</a> of pathologizing normal human behavior, which treatment providers could potentially exploit for profit; some argue that the proposed symptoms of <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/freedom-learn/201803/sense-and-nonsense-about-video-game-addiction">Internet gaming disorder may reflect passion for a hobby rather than a clinical condition.</a></p>
<p>Some argue that there is not enough compelling evidence for a <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/mind-matters-menninger/202106/behavioral-addiction-what-we-know-and-what-we-don-t">gaming addiction and its discerning criteria</a>. An addiction may reflect underlying psychological conditions that problem gamers are likely to have, suggesting that <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/i-hear-you/202007/there-s-no-such-thing-video-game-addiction-right">gaming disorder is not a discrete condition.</a></p>
      
        </div>
      </div>
      </div>

            </div>
                                                                <div class="faq faq--2">
                <div itemscope  itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
          <div class="faq--title d-flex">
        <div itemprop="name" class="h3 faq--question">
          
            Is gaming disorder the same as a gaming addiction?
      
        </div>
        <div class="faq--control-container">
          <button class="faq--control">
            <div class="faq--control-icon">
              <svg width="13px" height="8px" viewBox="0 0 13 8" version="1.1"
     xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
     xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
                <!-- Generator: Sketch 46.2 (44496) - http://www.bohemiancoding.com/sketch -->
                <desc>Created with Sketch.</desc>
                <defs></defs>
                <g id="-small" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd">
                  <g id="Tests---Listing-Page---SM"
                     transform="translate(-490.000000, -597.000000)" fill="#2C2D30">
                    <g id="Left-col" transform="translate(74.000000, 162.000000)">
                      <g id="Table" transform="translate(0.000000, 426.000000)">
                        <polygon id="navigatedown"
                                 points="422.310547 16.3125 428.621094 10.0019531 427.62793 9 422.310547 14.3173828 416.993164 9 416 10.0019531"></polygon>
                      </g>
                    </g>
                  </g>
                </g>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div itemscope="" itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer" class="faq--answer">
        <div itemprop="text">
          
            <p>Colloquially, people tend to use gaming disorder and gaming addiction interchangeably. But some researchers believe the criteria and language put forth to diagnose <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/in-excess/201906/gaming-disorder-revisited">gaming disorder doesn&rsquo;t fully capture the nature of addiction</a>.</p>
      
        </div>
      </div>
      </div>

            </div>
                                                                <div class="faq faq--3 collapsed">
                <div itemscope  itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
          <div class="faq--title d-flex">
        <div itemprop="name" class="h3 faq--question">
          
            Does the video game industry view gaming as a disorder?
      
        </div>
        <div class="faq--control-container">
          <button class="faq--control">
            <div class="faq--control-icon">
              <svg width="13px" height="8px" viewBox="0 0 13 8" version="1.1"
     xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
     xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
                <!-- Generator: Sketch 46.2 (44496) - http://www.bohemiancoding.com/sketch -->
                <desc>Created with Sketch.</desc>
                <defs></defs>
                <g id="-small" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd">
                  <g id="Tests---Listing-Page---SM"
                     transform="translate(-490.000000, -597.000000)" fill="#2C2D30">
                    <g id="Left-col" transform="translate(74.000000, 162.000000)">
                      <g id="Table" transform="translate(0.000000, 426.000000)">
                        <polygon id="navigatedown"
                                 points="422.310547 16.3125 428.621094 10.0019531 427.62793 9 422.310547 14.3173828 416.993164 9 416 10.0019531"></polygon>
                      </g>
                    </g>
                  </g>
                </g>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div itemscope="" itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer" class="faq--answer">
        <div itemprop="text">
          
            <p>Both the gaming industry and gamers themselves have <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/making-meaning/201901/debate-over-gaming-disorder-is-not-all-fun-and-games">objected to the creation of a gaming disorder,</a> pointing to the lack of definitive evidence, risk of misdiagnosis, and the benefits that some derive from gaming. The industry is correct in pointing out the debates around behavioral addictions, although they may also be driven by self-interest.</p>
      
        </div>
      </div>
      </div>

            </div>
                                                                <div class="faq faq--4 collapsed">
                <div itemscope  itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
          <div class="faq--title d-flex">
        <div itemprop="name" class="h3 faq--question">
          
            How are behavioral addictions generally viewed?
      
        </div>
        <div class="faq--control-container">
          <button class="faq--control">
            <div class="faq--control-icon">
              <svg width="13px" height="8px" viewBox="0 0 13 8" version="1.1"
     xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
     xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
                <!-- Generator: Sketch 46.2 (44496) - http://www.bohemiancoding.com/sketch -->
                <desc>Created with Sketch.</desc>
                <defs></defs>
                <g id="-small" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd">
                  <g id="Tests---Listing-Page---SM"
                     transform="translate(-490.000000, -597.000000)" fill="#2C2D30">
                    <g id="Left-col" transform="translate(74.000000, 162.000000)">
                      <g id="Table" transform="translate(0.000000, 426.000000)">
                        <polygon id="navigatedown"
                                 points="422.310547 16.3125 428.621094 10.0019531 427.62793 9 422.310547 14.3173828 416.993164 9 416 10.0019531"></polygon>
                      </g>
                    </g>
                  </g>
                </g>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div itemscope="" itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer" class="faq--answer">
        <div itemprop="text">
          
            <p>Addictions have historically been defined by substances that lead to destructive behaviors in pursuit of the next fix. However, as technology has improved, f-MRI data along with mounting evidence suggests that <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/mind-matters-menninger/202106/behavioral-addiction-what-we-know-and-what-we-don-t">behavioral addictions</a> are more like substance addictions than initially believed; addiction resides not in the properties of a substance but the interaction between those properties and a person's vulnerability to addiction. A&nbsp;wide variety of behaviors can induce an addiction-like state that scientists debate where to draw the line between a coping mechanism, a symptom of another disorder, and addiction.</p>
      
        </div>
      </div>
      </div>

            </div>
                                                                <div class="faq faq--5 collapsed faq--last">
                <div itemscope  itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
          <div class="faq--title d-flex">
        <div itemprop="name" class="h3 faq--question">
          
            Does the DSM-5 include any behavioral addictions?
      
        </div>
        <div class="faq--control-container">
          <button class="faq--control">
            <div class="faq--control-icon">
              <svg width="13px" height="8px" viewBox="0 0 13 8" version="1.1"
     xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
     xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
                <!-- Generator: Sketch 46.2 (44496) - http://www.bohemiancoding.com/sketch -->
                <desc>Created with Sketch.</desc>
                <defs></defs>
                <g id="-small" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd">
                  <g id="Tests---Listing-Page---SM"
                     transform="translate(-490.000000, -597.000000)" fill="#2C2D30">
                    <g id="Left-col" transform="translate(74.000000, 162.000000)">
                      <g id="Table" transform="translate(0.000000, 426.000000)">
                        <polygon id="navigatedown"
                                 points="422.310547 16.3125 428.621094 10.0019531 427.62793 9 422.310547 14.3173828 416.993164 9 416 10.0019531"></polygon>
                      </g>
                    </g>
                  </g>
                </g>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div itemscope="" itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer" class="faq--answer">
        <div itemprop="text">
          
            <p><a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/conditions/gambling-disorder-compulsive-gambling-pathological-gambling">Gambling disorder</a> is the only behavioral addiction included in the DSM-5. But researchers and clinicians have long debated many others, including video gaming, Internet use, exercise, shopping, <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/sex" title="Psychology Today looks at sexual" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">sexual</a> behavior, <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/pornography" title="Psychology Today looks at porn" class="basics-link" hreflang="en-US">porn</a> use, and others.</p>
      
        </div>
      </div>
      </div>

            </div>
                        </div>

    
        
  </div>
</div>
          <div class="pt-ad pt-ad--300x250 d-block d-none d-md-block d-lg-none block" id="block-ad-subpage-300x250-programmatically-rendered">
  
    
      <div class="pt-ad--container pt-ad-show-text">
      <div class="pt-ad--text">
      <span>article continues after advertisement</span>
    </div>
